column1: How many new energy vehicles (NEVs) will be sold in China in 2020?
column5: ['Fewer than 800,000', 'Between 800,000 and 950,000, inclusive', 'More than 950,000 but less than 1,100,000', 'Between 1,100,000 and 1,250,000, inclusive', 'More than 1,250,000']
column6: ['Business', 'Technology', 'Environment']
Wish I paid more attention to this one.
I'm going all in: total 1,310,000 give or take 30K. Why? In every one of the last four years sales in December have exceeded those of November, and I can't see any indicator to suggest a major upset.
I’m going to be even more bullish on Chinese economic growth for December. Chinese stock went higher lifted by strong continued recovery signals in November

I realize the measurement is caam but slightly different numbers here (Nov not provided yet). regardless bumping up fifth bucket as I’m completely unsure of any year end impacts (pro or con). I really can’t tell on this one. https://www.statista.com/statistics/425458/china-monthly-new-energy-vehicle-sales-by-type/

November data adds 200K units for a total for the year of 1.1M units. Add an estimated 200K for December to yield 1.3M units for the year filling the last bucket. If only 150K units are sold in December it would be right on the bubble. Since I was all in on the fourth bucket before, I'll need to go all in on the fifth bucket to have a shot at this one.
NEV sales already over 1.1 million http://www.caam.org.cn/chn/21/cate_463/con_5232642.html
http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-12/06/c_139566834.htm

Numbers may be off slightly but believe ~890 through Oct. a couple decent mints easy gets to 1 100 - 1 250. June through Oct has seen 104, 98, 98, 138, 160... so a decent (as seems very likely) Nov will provide solid indicator.
Thru Sept 734K NEVs sold. Thru Oct 901K NEVs sold. Simple extrapolation yields 1.22M units by year end. GAME OVER

I think total will be very close to 1,100,000. Everything points towards China pushing ahead with production and sales now they are out of the first Covid-19 wave. I'm hedging slightly against earlier forecasts just under this break point.

I think the big question has now become whether the sales will exceed 1,100,000. Volumes look to be highest in the last quarter of each year, as a general trend over the last few years. And they increased noticeably over September from approx 100K/m over summer. If the last three months report similar levels we could be right on the break point. Overall there seems more likelihood of a downside than up, so I'm cautiously staying at around 1,080,000
NEV sales are accelerating from previous quarter. Could be near 1.1M units this year.
https://news.cgtn.com/news/2020-10-05/China-s-EV-sales-rebound-as-overall-market-continues-recovery-UkYyiA0D0A/index.html#

The numbers coming out exceeded my (prior) thoughts. Pushing 750 with 1/4 of year left. Points to something in 970-980 range even accounting for year end. Plus supply/demand increasing (not decreasing). Not sure how to factor increases. Regardless per others something close to 1 million
Thru Sept 734K NEVs sold. Simple extrapolation yields 978K units by year end. 1M units really looks achievable.

Based on the existing production and sales in Sep, Oct - Dec is likely to follow a similar trend, giving more weight to the nearer month sales, a range of 1 million to 1.15 is likely. Additional news based on Xi's commitment to climate change, this increases the likelihood where the political agenda improves the numbers.
Same view as from August 10th, as sales have picked up in the latter half of the year.

I'm still anticipating a 10-20% drop from 2019. I think the second half of this year will see similar figures to 2019, compared to a 30-40% drop in the first half. Continuing subsidies should help, along with the gradual trend away from fossil fuels, increasing climate concerns, and China's desire to keep manufacturing developing. Offset perhaps by cheaper oil prices and economic uncertainty.

I'm still anticipating a 10-20% drop from 2019 overall. I think the second half of this year will see similar figures to last years, making up somewhat for 3-40% drop in the first half. Continuing subsidies should help, along with the inexorable trend away from fossil fuels and greater climate concerns, offset perhaps by cheaper oil prices and economic uncertainty.

Adjusting my forecast to a narrower band. Outside of major distortions (second waves, natural disasters), China's EV market is right on track to cross the 950,000. Finally found a way to visualize why in this link:

Sales slowed by Covid-19, recovering, but perhaps not a quickly as we'd like. Bloomberg 9/11 - "While the Shanghai plant has helped Tesla grow in China this year, it hasn’t expanded as quickly as some expected. The company has said it has the capacity to produce 200,000 vehicles a year -- almost 17,000 a month -- and in August sold about 11,800 cars in the country."

Yoy is at 19.3 for july with overall Yoy at -32.8 now. This is a faster recovery than I expected after seeing the numbers for june. Unsure how much weight to give this as it might be an outlier, given the decline even in 2019 before the coronavirus was a thing. Forecast: 3|15|66|15|1. Crowd: 6|44|44|6|0 Corrected forecast: 3|18|65|13|1
moving towards crowd
I'll take an optimistic view. NEV's are good for the planet and government policy encourages them. And who wants public transport at this time?
Expecting roughly 10-15% drop based on reduced sales for first half of year
YoY sales have gone down rather than up in june compared to may from -23.5 to -33.1. Still this represents a slight overall recovery to -37.4 of last years production.
Only slowed due to Covid

According to the CAAM portal, production and sales of NEVs stand at 400,000. Currently it is catching up at 20%. However, the overall projection is 30% negative growth. Hence, at 10% growth rate, it may be above 800,000 and 20% growth, it can reach upto 1,200,000.

Last two years (2018 & 2019) it was 1.2-1.3mln new sales. I project a restart of the 2020 economy in 2021, so sales growth to resume or to at least sales to flatten out at previous years’ levels (i.e. of ~1.2mln). I will therefore split probability between more than 1.25mln, and 1.1-1.25mln, with more weight to the higher bracket. I still leave some space for reduced sales, possibly due to a persistently soft economy.
Sales volume reduction due to COVID-19 related sales drop
Hat tip to @V-Y- and the data from technode.
Tesla alone will easily contribute 800,000.
The Chinese will uptake electric vehicles due to the external pressures of retaliation over COVID-19
I can't say just yet, but it feels like our consensus is off. Tesla is expanding and just about everyone is getting in the game. Maybe I'm wrong.

According to the source cited in https://technode.com/2020/06/16/ev-industry-grapples-with-consensus-as-sales-fall-further-in-may/, https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/Hm8YWA0MQNznxCeiiVmepQ we have a drop of 23.5% to 82000, while there was a drop of 38.7% to 289.000 for the january to may time frame. This gives us total sales of around 734500 for june to december 2019.
Thanks to @V-Y- and @bobrown for their comments + provided sources [1,2,3].
Baseline was a bell curve around middle option (950-1,100k), simply downgrading from 1.2m because last year is negatively impacted by COVID

2019 sales were 1.2M without Chinese built TSLA's. While 2020 may be a slower year due to Covid impact on finances those who can afford may be eager to avoid public transport. Locally built TSLA's should also drive nation wide sales higher. Hedging for future impact of Covid-19 in China and on demand for Chinese exports.
